Part B

  • Brief Description:

Stationarity: - The series appears to be non-stationary. This is evident from the fluctuations in the mean over the years, with periods of increases followed by decreases. The ADF test supports that as well.

Trend: - Peak in the 1980s: The series exhibits a sharp increase leading up to the early 1980s, reaching its highest point during this decade. This peak could be indicative of significant economic or geopolitical events during that period. - Decline Post 1980s: After the peak, there’s a pronounced decline that continues until the early 2000s. - Stability (2000s - Mid 2010s): The series seems to stabilize for almost two decades, oscillating around a relatively constant mean. - Gradual Uptrend (Mid 2010s - 2023): There’s a subtle uptrend starting from the mid-2010s, suggesting a slow increase in rates.

Seasonality:

At a glance, the series does not display an overt seasonal pattern. However, finer granular analyses might be needed to ascertain any potential hidden seasonal effects. Noise:

There are visible short-term fluctuations throughout the series. Such noise could be due to transient economic events or other short-lived influences.

Volatility:

High Volatility (Late 1970s - Mid 1980s): The period leading up to the peak in the 1980s and shortly after exhibits high volatility, suggesting uncertainty or significant economic shifts. Reduced Volatility (2000s - Mid 2010s): The period of stability also sees diminished volatility, indicating a more predictable economic environment. Slight Increase in Volatility (Mid 2010s - 2023): Along with the subtle uptrend, there’s a slight increase in volatility, pointing to some economic changes or uncertainties during this period.

ARIMA Modeling SECTION

We need to log the series and plot:

Usually, in time series analysis, we log transform the data in order to linearize the exponential growth pattern and reduce heteroscedasticity. In this case, if the data was presented in percentage form (0-1) rather than floating point numbers, we would have implemented the LOGIT in order to make the data stationary. However, since the data was non-stationary and exhibited level-dependent volatility, we would take the logs as an attempt to make the data mean-reverting to fit an ARIMA model.

#Create a new log dataframe
log_rates_df <- data.frame(Date = index(rates_xts), Rate = coredata(log(rates_xts)))

gg <- ggplot(log_rates_df, aes(x = Date, y = Rate)) +  # Specify the data and mapping of aesthetics
  
  # Plot the line graph with a golden color
  geom_line(color = "goldenrod3") +
  # Define titles and labels for the plot
  labs(title = "Log Monthly Yields April 1953 to October 2023", y = "Percent", x = "Date") +
  
  # Use a minimalistic theme for the plot
  theme_minimal() 
  
print(gg)

#check stationarity
station <- lapply(log_rates_df[, "Rate", drop=FALSE], adf.test, alternative="stationary", k=0)
print(station)

Observation

The ACF shows a sharp drop after lag 1. Indicative of an MA(1) process The PACF plot has a sharp drop after lag 2. Indicative of an AR(2) process The autocorrelations are quickly dying out suggesting stationarity. Hinting towards an ARIMA (2,1,1)

Back-Testing ————

# Split the data into training and test sets
back <- length(rates_xts) * 5/7
full <- length(rates_xts) * 7/7
train_data2 <- rates_xts[1:back]
test_data2 <- rates_xts[1:full]

# Fit an ARIMA model to the training data
arima_model <- auto.arima(train_data2)  # Automatically select the best ARIMA model

forecast_arima <- forecast(arima_model, h = 242)

# Plot the forecast
plot(forecast_arima, main = "Market Yield on 10-Year US Treasuries (ARIMA Forecast)", xlab = "Date", ylab = "Percent", fcol = "goldenrod3", type = "l")

# Overlay the actual time series data
lines(test_data2, col = "blue", lwd = 2)

# Add a legend
legend("topright", legend = c("ARIMA Forecast", "Actual"), col = c("goldenrod3", "blue"), lty = 1, lwd = 2)

# Calculate accuracy metrics for the forecast
accuracy_metrics_arima <- accuracy(forecast_arima, test_data2[606:847])

# Print out the accuracy metrics
print(accuracy_metrics_arima)
##                        ME      RMSE       MAE          MPE      MAPE      MASE
## Training set  0.002036396 0.2590938 0.1797271   0.01639635  2.631428 0.9306854
## Test set     -1.523403668 1.8929078 1.5910512 -86.35484441 87.745116 8.2389826
##                     ACF1
## Training set 0.001988823
## Test set              NA

My evaluation of the ARIMA model’s performance through backtesting on both the training and test sets has yielded insightful results. The model demonstrates commendable fitting capability with the training data, as indicated by the low Mean Error (ME), Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), and Mean Absolute Error (MAE). Moreover, the Mean Percentage Error (MPE) and Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) for the training set are within acceptable bounds, suggesting that the model forecasts are, on average, aligned with the historical data.

However, when the same model is subjected to the test set, its performance diminishes significantly. The negative Mean Error suggests a systematic underestimation of the actual values. The RMSE and MAE are notably higher for the test set, pointing towards less accurate forecasts. The MAPE for the test set is particularly alarming, as it exceeds 100%, which raises concerns about the model’s applicability to unseen data. This could be attributed to potential outliers, zero values, or structural breaks in the test set that the model fails to account for.

The Mean Absolute Scaled Error (MASE) for the test set further corroborates the model’s inadequate forecasting ability in comparison to a naïve benchmark. The lack of first-lag autocorrelation in the training set residuals, as shown by the ACF1 value close to zero, does not carry over to the test set, for which the ACF1 has not been reported.

These observations suggest that while the ARIMA model fits the training data well, its utility in forecasting future values is questionable. The drastic shift in performance metrics from the training to the test set implies overfitting and calls for a careful review of the model selection process. It is recommended to explore more complex models, incorporate additional explanatory variables, or apply different data transformations. This would potentially improve the model’s predictive power and generalizability to new data.

Time Series Cross-Validation: Comparing auto.arima and ets

fets <- function(rates_xts_,h) {
  forecast(ets(rates_xts), h = h)
}
forecast_dates1 <- seq(from = as.Date("1953-04-01"), by ='month', length.out = 997)

farima <- function(rates_xts,h)
  forecast(auto.arima(rates_xts), h = h)

fcast_ets <- fets(rates_xts, 150)

fcast_arima <- farima(rates_xts, 150)

fcast_df <- data.frame( 
  Date = forecast_dates1[848:997],
  ets_forecasts = fcast_ets$mean,
  ets_lower = fcast_ets$lower[,'95%'],
  ets_upper = fcast_ets$upper[,'95%']
)
fcast_df_arima <- data.frame( 
  Date = forecast_dates1[848:997],
  arima_forecasts = fcast_arima$mean,
  arima_lower = fcast_arima$lower[,'95%'],
  arima_upper = fcast_arima$upper[,'95%']
)
fcast_df <- merge(fcast_df, fcast_df_arima, by = "Date")

ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = yield_df, aes(x = Date, y = forecast), color = "blue") + 
  geom_line(data = fcast_df, aes(x = Date, y = ets_forecasts), color = "red") +
  geom_line(data = fcast_df, aes(x = Date, y = arima_forecasts), color = "green") +
  geom_ribbon(data = fcast_df, aes(x = Date, ymin = ets_lower, ymax = ets_upper), fill = "red", alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_ribbon(data = fcast_df, aes(x = Date, ymin = arima_lower, ymax = arima_upper), fill = "green", alpha = 0.2) +
  labs(title = "Yield Curve with ETS and ARIMA Forecasts", x = "Date", y = "Value") +
  theme_minimal()
